ct crew dynamics), not open to new ideas (resistance to learning). No explicit stress handling info. Leadership suggests teamwork, but show-off may be negative.\n\nB: Very conscientious (reliability), handles stress very well (good), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (technical), weak memory for numbers (could be issue for calculations), makes nasty remarks about colleagues (bad teamwork/communication). Overall strong on stress and responsibility, but poor interpersonal.\n\nC: Can make correct decisions quickly (decision-making), difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork issue), egocentric (teamwork), not willing to further education (professional development), keeps calm in crisis (calmness), understands complicated technology (technical). Mixed: good decision and calm, but poor teamwork and development.\n\nD: Responds to unexpected events adequately (some stress handling), concentrates well, solves problems extremely well (technical), takes responsibility seriously (reliability), know-it-all (could be overconfident), hot temper (stress/crew). No explicit teamwork, but hot temper may affect crew. Good problem solving, responsibility.\n\nThus we need to weigh strengths vs weaknesses. Likely candidate B has strong stress handling and conscientiousness but poor teamwork. Candidate C has good calmness and decision-making but poor communication and development. Candidate A has strong anticipation and leadership but lacks stress info and is not open to new ideas. Candidate D has responsibility and problem solving but hot temper and know-it-all.\n\nWhich is best? Long-distance flights require calm under pressure, good decision-making, teamwork, communication, reliability. Stress handling is crucial. B handles stress well, but nasty remarks could be dangerous. C keeps calm, good decisions, but communication issues. A leadership but unknown stress. D responsibility but hot temper.\n\nProbably candidate C might be best if communication can be mitigated? But egocentric and communication difficulty are serious for crew. B's nasty remarks could be severe. D's hot temper also serious. A's show-off and closed to new ideas could affect safety.\n\nThus maybe candidate A's leadership and anticipation outweigh unknown stress? But lack of stress handling is risky.\n\nWe might ask other agents for missing info: e.g., ask Agent 1 about Candidate B's teamwork/communication, or about Candidate C's stress handling, or about Candidate D's stress handling. But we already have B handles stress well (given). We have B's nasty remarks (bad). For D, we have hot temper (bad). For C, we have calm in crisis (good). So we have enough.\n\nThus we can make a vote. Which candidate seems best overall? Let's compare:\n\n- Reliability/responsibility: A (leadership), B (conscientious), C (not willing to further education but not a reliability issue), D (takes responsibility seriously).\n\n- Technical competence: A (spatial vision, complex connections), B (weather, computer), C (technology), D (problem solving).\n\n- Calmness/pressure: B (handles stress well), C (keeps calm in crisis), D (responds adequately), A unknown.\n\n- Decision-making: C (quick correct decisions), A (anticipate dangerous), D (problem solving), B (weather assessment).\n\n- Teamwork/communication: A (leadership but show-off), B (nasty remarks), C (difficulty communicating, egocentric), D (know-it-all, hot temper). All have issues.\n\n- Professional development: B (conscientious maybe good), C (not willing to further education), A (not open to new ideas), D (know-it-all maybe not open).\n\nThus each has pros and cons. Which is most balanced? B has strong stress handling and conscientiousness, but interpersonal issues severe. C has calmness and decision-making but communication issues. A has leadership and anticipation but unknown stress and closed mindset. D has responsibility and problem solving but hot temper.\n\nMaybe candidate A's leadership and anticipation are c