s colleagues (teamwork negative)\n\nC:\n- can make correct decisions quickly (decision-making)\n- difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork negative)\n- regarded as egocentric (teamwork negative)\n- not very willing to further his education (development)\n- keeps calm in a crisis (stress handling)\n- understands complicated technology (technical)\n\nD:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately (stress handling)\n- can concentrate very well (cognitive)\n- solves problems extremely well (technical)\n- takes responsibility seriously (reliability)\n- regarded as a know\u2011it\u2011all (potential overconfidence)\n- has a hot temper (teamwork/pressure negative)\n\nNo explicit teamwork/communication.\n\nNow weigh for long-distance pilot: need reliability, stress handling, decision-making, technical competence, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nCandidate B: strong stress handling, conscientious, but poor teamwork (nasty remarks) and weak memory for numbers (could be issue). Might be mitigated? But interpersonal is critical.\n\nCandidate C: calm under crisis, good decision, technical, but poor communication and egocentric, not willing to further education (development). Could be problematic.\n\nCandidate D: responsibility, problem solving, concentration, but hot temper and know-it-all could affect crew. Stress handling is only \"adequately\". Not strong.\n\nCandidate A: strong anticipation, leadership, spatial vision, but unknown stress handling, and negative traits (show-off, not open to new ideas, unorganized). Leadership suggests teamwork, but show-off may affect crew.\n\nThus each has trade-offs. Which is best? Possibly Candidate C's calmness and decision-making are crucial, but communication issues are severe. Candidate B's stress handling is crucial, but interpersonal negativity is also severe. Candidate D's hot temper is severe. Candidate A's unknown stress handling is a gap; but leadership may offset. However, not open to new ideas could hinder a